Explain Java Map Framework in COMPLETE depth from beginner to advanced level with internal working, real-world examples, memory concepts, performance analysis, and interview questions.

Cover EVERYTHING in detail.

# 1. Introduction to Map
- What is Map in Java?
A Map in Java is a data structure that stores data in the form of:
Key → Value
Each key is used to access its corresponding value.
Syntax
Map<KeyType, ValueType> map = new HashMap<>();


- Why Map is NOT part of Collection interface
This is one of the MOST IMPORTANT interview questions.

Collection Stores ONLY Values
Collection framework interfaces like:
List
Set
Queue
store ONLY individual elements.
Example:

List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

list.add("A");
list.add("B");

Here only values are stored.

But Map Stores Key + Value Pair
Example:
Map<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();

map.put(101, "Rahul");
Map stores:

101 → Rahul
So its structure is completely different from Collection.

- Difference between Collection and Map

| Feature          | Collection         | Map                  |
| ---------------- | ------------------ | -------------------- |
| Stores           | Only values        | Key-value pairs      |
| Duplicate values | Depends on type    | Values can duplicate |
| Duplicate keys   | Not applicable     | NOT allowed          |
| Access data      | By index/iterator  | By key               |
| Main interfaces  | List, Set, Queue   | Map                  |
| Example          | ArrayList, HashSet | HashMap, TreeMap     |

- Key-Value pair concept
- Real-world examples of Map


| Method          | Purpose       |
| --------------- | ------------- |
| put()           | Insert        |
| get()           | Retrieve      |
| remove()        | Delete        |
| containsKey()   | Check key     |
| containsValue() | Check value   |
| size()          | Count entries |
| clear()         | Remove all    |


