# 3. HashMap Deep Internal Working (VERY IMPORTANT)
Explain EVERYTHING internally.

Topics:
- Hashing concept
HashMap provides:

Fast insertion
Fast searching
Fast deletion
Internal Data Structure

Internally HashMap uses:

Array of Nodes (Buckets)

Each bucket can contain:

Single node
Linked List
Red-Black Tree (Java 8+)
Hashing Concept
Hashing converts a key into an integer value.

Example:

String key = "JAVA";

int hash = key.hashCode();

This hash helps determine:

Where data should be stored in array

- hashCode()
 every object has hashcode()
 String s="Java"
 System.out.println(s.hashcode());

- equals()
Used to compare actual objects.

Example:

String a = new String("JAVA");
String b = new String("JAVA");


System.out.println(a.equals(b)); // true

HashMap uses:

hashCode() → find bucket
equals() → find exact key


- Bucket concept
HashMap divides storage into buckets.

Example:

Bucket 0
Bucket 1
Bucket 2
Bucket 3

Each bucket is one index of array.

- Index calculation
HashMap calculates index using:

index = (n - 1) & hash

Where:

n = capacity
& = bitwise AND
  example: capacity 15=01111
  hash=19
  19=10011
  10011
  01111
  -----
  00011 = 3 (bucket 3)


- Collision
Collision occurs when:

Different keys generate same bucket index

Example:

"A" -> Bucket 3
"B" -> Bucket 3

Both stored in same bucket.

- Separate Chaining
To handle collision:

HashMap uses:

Separate Chaining

Meaning:

Linked List inside bucket

- Linked List in bucket
- Red-Black Tree conversion
- Why TREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 8
- Why UNTREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 6
- Resize operation
- Rehashing
-treeify example:
Bucket 3

A -> B -> C -> D -> E -> F -> G -> H

          D
        /   \
       B     F
      / \   / \
     A   C E   G
                \
                 H

- Load Factor
Load factor determines:

When resizing should happen

Default:

0.75
- Capacity
- Threshold formula: threshold = capacity * loadFactor
 16 * 0.75 = 12(After 12 elements Resize happens)
- Power of 2 capacity
- Bitwise AND optimization
- Why HashMap is fast
Because:

Direct bucket access using hash

Instead of searching entire data.

Without hashing:

O(n)

With hashing:

O(1)

- Time complexity

