# 7. LinkedHashMap Deep Dive
EWhat is LinkedHashMap?

 LinkedHashMap is a subclass of HashMap that:

 Stores key-value pairs
 Maintains order
 Uses:
 Hash Table
 Doubly Linked List
 LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();
 Internal Structure

 Internally:

 HashMap + Doubly Linked List

 It extends HashMap.

 Each node contains:

 class Entry<K,V> extends HashMap.Node<K,V> {
     Entry<K,V> before, after;
 }

 So every node has:

 key
 value
 hash
 next (bucket chain)
 before
 after
 Internal Diagram
 Bucket Array
 ------------------------------------------------

 index 2
    |
    v
  [A=10] ---> [B=20]

 index 5
    |
    v
  [C=30]

 ------------------------------------------------

 Doubly Linked List (Insertion Order)

 HEAD
   |
   v
 [A=10] <--> [B=20] <--> [C=30]
                                ^
                                |
                              TAIL
 Why Doubly Linked List?

 To maintain:

 insertion order
 OR
 access order
 Insertion Order

 Default behavior:

 LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map =
         new LinkedHashMap<>();

 Maintains order of insertion.

 Example:

 map.put(3, "C");
 map.put(1, "A");
 map.put(2, "B");

 System.out.println(map);

 Output:

 {3=C, 1=A, 2=B}
 Access Order

 Can maintain access order instead.

 LinkedHashMap<Integer, String> map =
     new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true);

 Third parameter:

 accessOrder = true

 Now recently accessed element moves to end.

 Example:

 map.get(1);

 Node 1 becomes most recently used.

 Access Order Diagram

 Before:

 1 <-> 2 <-> 3

 After get(1):

 2 <-> 3 <-> 1
 LRU Cache Implementation

 LRU = Least Recently Used

 Most common use of LinkedHashMap.

 How LRU Works

 When cache is full:

 Remove least recently used item
 Keep recently accessed items
 removeEldestEntry()

 Special method:

 protected boolean removeEldestEntry(
         Map.Entry<K,V> eldest)

 Called after insertion.

 If returns true:

 Oldest entry removed automatically
 LRU Cache Example
 import java.util.*;

 class LRUCache<K,V> extends LinkedHashMap<K,V> {

     private final int capacity;

     public LRUCache(int capacity) {
         super(capacity, 0.75f, true);
         this.capacity = capacity;
     }

     @Override
     protected boolean removeEldestEntry(
             Map.Entry<K,V> eldest) {

         return size() > capacity;
     }
 }

 public class Main {
     public static void main(String[] args) {

         LRUCache<Integer,String> cache =
                 new LRUCache<>(3);

         cache.put(1, "A");
         cache.put(2, "B");
         cache.put(3, "C");

         cache.get(1);

         cache.put(4, "D");

         System.out.println(cache);
     }
 }

 Output:

 {3=C, 1=A, 4=D}

 2=B removed because least recently used.

 Real-World Use Cases
 1. LRU Cache

 Used in:

 Browsers
 Databases
 Redis-like systems
 2. Maintaining Request Order

 Example:

 API request logs
 3. Recently Viewed Products

 E-commerce websites.

 Time Complexity
 Operation	Complexity
 put()	O(1)
 get()	O(1)
 remove()	O(1)

 LinkedHashMap vs HashMap
 | Feature          | HashMap         | LinkedHashMap   |
 | ---------------- | --------------- | --------------- |
 | Ordering         | No              | Yes             |
 | Extra Memory     | Less            | More            |
 | Performance      | Slightly Faster | Slightly Slower |
 | Uses Linked List | No              | Yes             |

# 8. TreeMap Deep Dive
Explain:
